http://www.3dhubs.com/cambridge/hubs/wayne

3D scans are a great way to share cultural heritage with the world. I mainly use photogrammetry and Memento beta from Autodesk. Scientist working in USA passionate of computer graphic and science simulation and visualization. I started doing computer grqphic at 19, in 1993. Passing from POV-RAY to LightWave, Houdini, 3DStudio, 3DS Max, Blender. In 2014, I have started 3D scanning with first a Kinect from Microsoft and afterward moved to photogrammetry. Photogrammetry is more flexible and I use mainly CapturingReality and ReCap Pro from AutoDesk. In 2015, I started 3D printing with a Solidoodle Press.
Electronic engineer used to prototype various products.

Geeky baker using 3D tech to enhance my life in general and to help me make amazing cakes, cookies, candies, etc in particular. :) I was doing a degree in software when I developed meningitis (2012), so my learning curve now is a bit slower than it was, but still enjoying keeping up to date as much as money will allow and my brain can manage. My computing and my baking both combine my love of creating and my love of art. Being unique or ahead of the crowd is so much nicer than being the one following behind with the shovel. Lame internet access impedes matters a bit, but hey, I'm hoping this year to get myself a makerbot and see where I can go from there. Already using die cutters (manual and printer cutters) with chocolate and fondant and doing my own edible printing with chocolate transfer sheets and icing sheets; 3D can only see things get better and better with the chance to make moulds and cutters unique to me and my own style as well as mounts and frames for ever more inventive cakes. We own the last wood fired bread oven in old Nice, I make my own chocolate - no, I don't just melt it into new shapes, I buy organic, washed beans and go from there. I create recipes all the time and do all my own design work and artwork for the bakery as well as for the cakes and other things we sell. I love the past as much as the new and can never learn things fast enough to keep me happy and amused. Martial arts helps me stay focussed and calm when stressed or frustrated and himself and the fur faced creatures keep me grounded when I get too excited. Nothing like emptying the litter tray to bring you down to reality. The Cote d'Azur is a tech ground zero - that is it's a huge hole in the ground where nothing will ever grow. Stone age about covers it, so I'm always looking to the UK or US for updates and information. It's that or go (more) insane. Fortunately I have good friends in lots of fields in a lot of countries, so I never want for inspiration, new ideas or cutting edge geekery. Sci fi, Trek more than Wars, but both are good. bio:
I moved to Deep Ellum to get a fresh start from my previous life. Several of my new friends from the area were in the street art/modern art scene back in 2008. Of course I wanted to try my hand at it as well, but it was not my creative outlet. So instead of putting stuff out that was not cool, I stopped trying to paint and focused on building a Digital Studio. I was recording, and burning DVD's for local poets, and started editing loops for a VJ. Still I wanted to take it further so I started learning how to animate in both 2D & 3D. Animation was really the turning point for me. It started out with that was all I did everyday after work. I quit drinking and my want to do something more grew. So I started messing around with Raspberry PI's . That lead to wanting to control lights, servos, and all that mechanical candy. I found a digital community and there is where I started hearing about 3D printing. I was hooked. I read everything I could on 3D printing and finally bought a printrbot Simple Kit 1405. My dad came over and helped me the first day, then I finished putting it together the next day and was printing shortly there after. After a year I upgraded to printrbot metal plus and well here I am today.

YOU CAN ALSO CHECK OUT: https://dehammer.myportfolio.com/

bio: Make Stuff!

I'm a programmer/wanna-be inventor. I used to do a bit of woodworking, and I did some 3d graphics as well, so when I heard about 3d printing, I was hooked. Since then it's been my new hobby. I love to design things. I've built all kinds of stuff with the printer, but most were specific to things I was doing around the house (which includes parts for furniture, some mounts for raspberry pis etc.). I've posted a few designs on thingiverse. I recently posted a design for a Cold Hold, which hasn't gained a lot of traction on thingiverse, but is still my favorite design. If you're reading this, please check it out.

I'm on my second printer -- my first being a BFB Rapman, which was quite good at the time, but the threaded rods warped (badly), the bed wore out, one of the extruders failed, and so I've since upgraded to a Craftbot. I'm down to around 1 in 20 failure rate, as opposed to a 1 in 3 from the Rapman, and it prints a lot smoother, so I'm quite happy with it. Anyways, I'm working on several new things, and hopefully, I'll have more to post on thingiverse shortly.

Good introduction into printer engineering and mechanics...
